&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Photosynthesis&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Photosynthesis&lt;/strong&gt; is an &lt;strong&gt;endothermic reaction&lt;/strong&gt;, meaning it absorbs energy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this process, plants use &lt;strong&gt;sunlight&lt;/strong&gt; to convert &lt;strong&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;water&lt;/strong&gt; into &lt;strong&gt;glucose&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;oxygen&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It requires the input of &lt;strong&gt;light energy&lt;/strong&gt; from the sun, which is absorbed by &lt;strong&gt;chlorophyll&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Since it absorbs energy rather than releasing it, photosynthesis is not exothermic.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This process is crucial for producing &lt;strong&gt;organic compounds&lt;/strong&gt; and maintaining the &lt;strong&gt;oxygen levels&lt;/strong&gt; in the atmosphere.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dilution of a strong acid&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is an &lt;strong&gt;exothermic reaction&lt;/strong&gt; as it releases heat when the strong acid is diluted with water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Respiration&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Respiration is an &lt;strong&gt;exothermic process&lt;/strong&gt; because it releases energy by breaking down glucose in the presence of oxygen.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Burning of natural gas&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The burning of natural gas is a highly &lt;strong&gt;exothermic reaction&lt;/strong&gt;, releasing a significant amount of heat and light energy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Natural gas primarily consists of &lt;strong&gt;methane&lt;/strong&gt; which combusts to produce &lt;strong&gt;carbon dioxide&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;water&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;H+ ion concentration&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The pH scale is used to measure the concentration of hydrogen ions (H+) in a solution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;pH is a logarithmic scale ranging from 0 to 14, where 7 is neutral, below 7 is acidic, and above 7 is basic or alkaline.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The pH value is calculated as the negative logarithm of the hydrogen ion concentration: pH = -log[H+].&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Acidic solutions have higher concentrations of H+ ions, while basic solutions have lower concentrations of H+ ions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The pH scale is crucial in chemistry, biology, environmental science, and various industrial processes to determine the acidity or basicity of substances.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Neutral pH:&lt;/strong&gt; A pH of 7 indicates a neutral solution, such as pure water, where the concentration of H+ ions equals the concentration of OH- ions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acidic Solutions:&lt;/strong&gt; Solutions with a pH less than 7 are acidic, meaning they have a higher concentration of H+ ions. Examples include lemon juice and vinegar.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Basic (Alkaline) Solutions:&lt;/strong&gt; Solutions with a pH greater than 7 are basic or alkaline, meaning they have a lower concentration of H+ ions and a higher concentration of OH- ions. Examples include baking soda and ammonia.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;pH Indicators:&lt;/strong&gt; Substances like litmus paper, phenolphthalein, and bromothymol blue are used to visually determine the pH of a solution by changing color in response to its acidity or basicity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Environmental Impact:&lt;/strong&gt; pH levels are critical in environmental science, affecting aquatic life, soil health, and chemical reactions in ecosystems. Maintaining a balanced pH is essential for the health of natural water bodies and agricultural land.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;either positive or negative&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The work done by a &lt;strong&gt;constant force&lt;/strong&gt; on a body depends on the &lt;strong&gt;direction of the force&lt;/strong&gt; relative to the direction of the &lt;strong&gt;displacement&lt;/strong&gt; of the body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the force is in the same direction as the displacement, the work done is &lt;strong&gt;positive&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the force is in the opposite direction to the displacement, the work done is &lt;strong&gt;negative&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When the force and displacement are perpendicular to each other, the work done is &lt;strong&gt;zero&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the work done by a constant force can be &lt;strong&gt;positive, negative, or zero&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;always zero&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This option is incorrect because the work done by a constant force is not always zero.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Work done can be zero only if the force is perpendicular to the displacement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;always positive&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This option is incorrect because the work done by a constant force is not always positive.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Work done is positive only if the force is in the same direction as the displacement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;always negative&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This option is incorrect because the work done by a constant force is not always negative.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Work done is negative only if the force is in the opposite direction to the displacement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;vacuoles&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Meristematic cells are known for their high metabolic activity and continuous division.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These cells lack vacuoles, which are generally present in mature plant cells.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The absence of vacuoles allows meristematic cells to maintain a dense cytoplasm essential for rapid cell division.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Meristematic cells have thin cell walls made of cellulose, which facilitate their growth and division.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These cells also contain prominent nuclei to support their high levels of genetic activity.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Meristematic Tissue&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a type of plant tissue consisting of undifferentiated cells capable of cell division.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Meristematic tissues are found in regions of the plant where growth can take place, such as the tips of roots and shoots.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These tissues are classified into apical, lateral, and intercalary meristems based on their location and function.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Vacuoles&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Vacuoles are membrane-bound organelles found in the cytoplasm of plant cells and some protists.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are involved in storing nutrients, waste products, and helping maintain turgor pressure within the cell.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In mature plant cells, vacuoles can occupy up to 90% of the cell&amp;#39;s volume.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cell Division&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Cell division in plants primarily occurs through mitosis in meristematic tissues.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mitosis ensures that each daughter cell receives an identical set of chromosomes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is crucial for plant growth, development, and repair.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cellulose&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Cellulose is a complex carbohydrate that constitutes the primary cell wall of green plants.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It provides structural support to the plant cell.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Thin cellulose walls in meristematic cells allow for flexibility and rapid expansion during cell division.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Urethra - a pair&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;urethra&lt;/strong&gt; is a tube that carries urine from the &lt;strong&gt;urinary bladder&lt;/strong&gt; to the outside of the body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In males, the urethra also carries &lt;strong&gt;semen&lt;/strong&gt; during ejaculation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Humans have a &lt;strong&gt;single urethra&lt;/strong&gt;, which is unpaired.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The female urethra is approximately &lt;strong&gt;4 cm long&lt;/strong&gt;, while the male urethra is about &lt;strong&gt;20 cm long&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The urethra opens at the &lt;strong&gt;external urethral orifice&lt;/strong&gt;, which is located at the tip of the penis in males and above the vaginal opening in females.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ureter&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;ureters&lt;/strong&gt; are a pair of tubes that carry urine from the &lt;strong&gt;kidneys&lt;/strong&gt; to the &lt;strong&gt;urinary bladder&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Each human body has a pair of ureters, one attached to each kidney.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The ureters are approximately &lt;strong&gt;25-30 cm long&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They enter the urinary bladder at an oblique angle to prevent the backflow of urine.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kidney&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Humans have a pair of &lt;strong&gt;kidneys&lt;/strong&gt;, which are vital organs for filtering blood and producing urine.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Each kidney is located on either side of the spine, just below the rib cage.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Kidneys help in removing waste products and excess substances from the blood.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They also regulate electrolyte balance and blood pressure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Urinary bladder&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;urinary bladder&lt;/strong&gt; is a hollow, muscular organ that stores urine until it is excreted.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is located in the pelvis, just above and behind the pubic bone.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The bladder can hold between &lt;strong&gt;300-500 mL&lt;/strong&gt; of urine.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When it is full, stretch receptors in the bladder signal the brain to initiate the urge to urinate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Soaps molecules have two ends &amp;mdash; one is hydrophilic and the other end is hydrophobic.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Soap molecules consist of two distinct ends: a hydrophilic (water-attracting) end and a hydrophobic (water-repelling) end.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The hydrophilic end is typically a carboxylate ion (&amp;ndash;COO&lt;sup&gt;-&lt;/sup&gt;) that dissolves in water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The hydrophobic end is usually a long hydrocarbon chain that interacts with oils and grease.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This dual-end structure allows soaps to emulsify fats and oils, effectively removing dirt and grease from surfaces.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Detergents work similarly to soaps but can be more effective in hard water conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydrophilic:&lt;/strong&gt; This term refers to the affinity of a molecule or substance to interact with or dissolve in water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydrophobic:&lt;/strong&gt; This term describes the tendency of a molecule or substance to repel water or not mix with water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Emulsification:&lt;/strong&gt; The process by which soap or detergent molecules surround oil or grease particles, breaking them into smaller droplets that can be washed away with water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hard Water:&lt;/strong&gt; Water that contains high concentrations of calcium and magnesium ions, which can reduce the effectiveness of soap and form scum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Detergents:&lt;/strong&gt; Synthetic cleaning agents similar to soap but are more effective in hard water and can be designed for specific cleaning tasks.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;power&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Power&lt;/strong&gt; is defined as the rate at which work is done or energy is transferred over time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is measured in &lt;strong&gt;watts (W)&lt;/strong&gt; in the International System of Units (SI).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;One watt is equal to one joule per second (1 W = 1 J/s).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Power can also be expressed in other units like horsepower (1 hp = 746 W) and kilowatts (1 kW = 1000 W).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Work&lt;/strong&gt;:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Work is the amount of energy transferred by a force over a distance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is measured in joules (J) in the SI system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The formula for work is W = F &amp;times; d, where W is work, F is force, and d is distance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Energy&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Energy is the capacity to do work.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is also measured in joules (J).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Different forms of energy include kinetic energy, potential energy, thermal energy, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Force&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Force is any interaction that, when unopposed, will change the motion of an object.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is measured in newtons (N) in the SI system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Newton&amp;#39;s second law states that F = m &amp;times; a, where F is force, m is mass, and a is acceleration.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Horsepower&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Horsepower is a unit of measurement for power, commonly used to measure the power of engines.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;One horsepower is equivalent to 746 watts.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It was developed by James Watt to compare the output of steam engines to the power of draft horses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;18 N&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The weight of an object is the force with which it is attracted towards the center of a celestial body due to gravity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The gravitational force on the Moon is approximately 1/6th of that on the Earth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If an object weighs 3 N on the Moon, it means the same object weighs 3 N / (1/6) = 18 N on Earth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The acceleration due to gravity on the Earth&amp;#39;s surface is about 9.81 m/s&amp;sup2;, whereas on the Moon, it is about 1.63 m/s&amp;sup2;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gravitational Force&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is the force that attracts two bodies towards each other, dependent on their masses and the distance between them.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The gravitational force is described by Newton&amp;#39;s Law of Gravitation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Weight vs. Mass&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Weight is the force exerted by gravity on an object, measured in Newtons (N).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mass is the amount of matter in an object, measured in kilograms (kg), and is constant regardless of location.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gravitational Acceleration&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The acceleration due to gravity on Earth is approximately 9.81 m/s&amp;sup2;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Moon&amp;#39;s gravity is roughly 1/6th of Earth&amp;#39;s, about 1.63 m/s&amp;sup2;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Surface Gravity&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Surface gravity affects how much an object weighs on a planet or moon.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It varies depending on the celestial body&amp;#39;s mass and radius.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Helps the cells to grow longer&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Auxins&lt;/strong&gt; are a class of plant hormones that play a crucial role in the &lt;strong&gt;growth and development&lt;/strong&gt; of plants.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are primarily involved in the &lt;strong&gt;elongation of cells&lt;/strong&gt; in the shoots and roots.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Auxins stimulate cell elongation by &lt;strong&gt;loosening the cell walls&lt;/strong&gt;, which allows the cells to take up more water and expand.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are also involved in various other plant growth processes such as &lt;strong&gt;apical dominance&lt;/strong&gt;, root initiation, and &lt;strong&gt;fruit development&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Auxins are produced in the &lt;strong&gt;apical meristems&lt;/strong&gt; (growth regions at the tips of roots and shoots) and are transported to other parts of the plant where they exert their effects.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;One of the most well-known auxins is &lt;strong&gt;Indole-3-acetic acid (IAA)&lt;/strong&gt;, which is naturally occurring in plants.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Make plants insect resistant&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This function is not related to auxins. Instead, &lt;strong&gt;plant resistance to insects&lt;/strong&gt; is often achieved through genetic modifications or breeding techniques that increase the plant&amp;rsquo;s natural defenses.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Increases stem width&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Increasing stem width is primarily influenced by another class of plant hormones called &lt;strong&gt;gibberellins&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;cytokinins&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Induce flowering&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While auxins are involved in many growth processes, the induction of flowering is mainly regulated by &lt;strong&gt;florigen&lt;/strong&gt; and other specific flowering hormones.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;v&amp;sup2; - u&amp;sup2; = 2gh&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The equation &lt;strong&gt;v&amp;sup2; - u&amp;sup2; = 2gh&lt;/strong&gt; is derived from the kinematic equations of motion, which are fundamental in physics for describing the motion of objects.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this context, &lt;strong&gt;u&lt;/strong&gt; represents the initial velocity of the object, &lt;strong&gt;v&lt;/strong&gt; is the final velocity, &lt;strong&gt;g&lt;/strong&gt; is the acceleration due to gravity, and &lt;strong&gt;h&lt;/strong&gt; is the height from which the object falls.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This equation assumes that the only force acting on the object is gravity, meaning air resistance and other forces are negligible.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The formula is particularly useful for calculating the final velocity of an object in free fall when the initial velocity and height are known.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kinematic Equations:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These are equations that describe the motion of objects without considering the causes of the motion.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are crucial in solving problems related to uniformly accelerated motion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acceleration due to Gravity (g):&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The standard value of gravitational acceleration on Earth is approximately 9.81 m/s&amp;sup2;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a constant that is used in various calculations involving free-falling objects.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Free Fall:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is the motion of a body where gravity is the only force acting upon it.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In a vacuum, all objects fall at the same rate regardless of their mass.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Initial and Final Velocity:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Initial velocity (u) is the velocity of the object before it starts falling.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Final velocity (v) is the velocity of the object just before it hits the ground or stops accelerating.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
